WEBVTT
Kind: captions
Language: en

00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:07.790
&gt;&gt; Well, thank you very much everybody for
being here.

00:00:07.790 --> 00:00:11.330
I don't think our special guest today needs
much of an introduction.

00:00:11.330 --> 00:00:16.129
But I hope most of you, all of you know, Cherie
Blair.

00:00:16.129 --> 00:00:19.579
Cherie's a barrister and a part-time judge
whose focus is public law

00:00:19.579 --> 00:00:24.140
and human rights.
She practices in many UK courts as well as

00:00:24.140 --> 00:00:25.650
the European Court of
Justice.

00:00:25.650 --> 00:00:29.060
Mother of four.
Very passionate about women's rights issues,

00:00:29.060 --> 00:00:31.109
women's inequality,
religious freedom.

00:00:31.109 --> 00:00:40.719
A whole bunch of other stuff.
And also is the wife of our prior Prime Minister

00:00:40.719 --> 00:00:45.809
for ten years -- Prime
Minister for ten years, not wife for ten years.

00:00:45.809 --> 00:00:48.940
CHERIE BLAIR: No, wife 29 years on Sunday.

00:00:48.940 --> 00:00:50.109
&gt;&gt; 29 on Sunday.

00:00:50.109 --> 00:00:54.410
CHERIE BLAIR: This last Sunday. We just had
our 29th anniversary.

00:00:54.410 --> 00:00:55.410
&gt;&gt; Congratulations.
[APPLAUSE]

00:00:55.410 --> 00:00:58.219
CHERIE BLAIR: How many years have you been
married?

00:00:58.219 --> 00:00:59.219
&gt;&gt;18.

00:00:59.219 --> 00:01:00.260
CHERIE BLAIR: 18. Not bad.

00:01:00.260 --> 00:01:02.980
&gt;&gt; That's not bad.
I'll never catch up though.

00:01:02.980 --> 00:01:05.019
You'll always be 20 years ahead.

00:01:05.019 --> 00:01:08.070
CHERIE BLAIR: That's just cause I'm older
than you.

00:01:08.070 --> 00:01:10.109
Not perhaps as much as --
[LAUGHTER]

00:01:10.109 --> 00:01:14.509
&gt;&gt; We won't go there.
She also has a First Class degree of London

00:01:14.509 --> 00:01:19.520
School of Economics, which I found very fascinating.
But more importantly, she's recently written

00:01:19.520 --> 00:01:24.240
a book called Speaking for
Myself, which was published in May 2008.

00:01:24.240 --> 00:01:26.540
And the paperback version comes out soon.

00:01:26.540 --> 00:01:27.909
CHERIE BLAIR: In June.

00:01:27.909 --> 00:01:30.060
&gt;&gt; In June.
And a Chinese version comes out --

00:01:30.060 --> 00:01:31.499
CHERIE BLAIR: Also in the summer.

00:01:31.499 --> 00:01:32.499
&gt;&gt; Fantastic.
Wonderful.

00:01:32.499 --> 00:01:37.070
And has been on the bestseller list many different
places, I noticed.

00:01:37.070 --> 00:01:41.399
So I was telling Cherie earlier, I've read
17 -- I've never done this

00:01:41.399 --> 00:01:42.399
before.

00:01:42.399 --> 00:01:43.399
CHERIE BLAIR: Haven't you?

00:01:43.399 --> 00:01:46.829
&gt;&gt; You've done this at least -- I saw four
videos on YouTube, where

00:01:46.829 --> 00:01:48.820
you've done it.
So at least you've done it four times.

00:01:48.820 --> 00:01:53.540
I know you've done it a lot more times.
So we're going to talk about the book we're

00:01:53.540 --> 00:01:57.390
going to talk about issues
that Cherie is passionate about.

00:01:57.390 --> 00:02:00.650
And she's promised to talk about technology
because she's a

00:02:00.650 --> 00:02:07.530
self-proclaimed geek, so she says.
So why don't we start with your book, if that's

00:02:07.530 --> 00:02:08.530
good.

00:02:08.530 --> 00:02:11.930
CHERIE BLAIR: Well, actually, funny enough,
When I came in here, I didn't know I was going

00:02:11.930 --> 00:02:14.440
to be talking about the
book on a beach.

00:02:14.440 --> 00:02:18.519
And I see all of you certainly as though you're
on a beach.

00:02:18.519 --> 00:02:22.859
I'm, on the other hand, seem to be in a bit
more in the sort of more

00:02:22.859 --> 00:02:23.859
business --

00:02:23.859 --> 00:02:25.109
&gt;&gt; I think that we would be a lot more comfortable
for us to use.

00:02:25.109 --> 00:02:29.299
CHERIE BLAIR: Funny enough, the book -- I
wanted to write a book which

00:02:29.299 --> 00:02:46.630
actually you might like to read on a beach.
There was a lot of publicity at the time about

00:02:46.630 --> 00:02:55.880
my book and what it was
going to be about.

00:02:55.880 --> 00:03:02.510
And it was going to be some sort of political
diatribe.

00:03:02.510 --> 00:03:25.380
That was never what I wanted to do.
And that's not what the book's about.

00:03:25.380 --> 00:03:41.209
It's actually a woman's book.
It's a story of a woman who's in her 50s.

00:03:41.209 --> 00:03:52.959
Who in a 50-year journey has come on a journey
which isn't unique.

00:03:52.959 --> 00:04:06.890
Though in the end, she ended up at 10 Downing
Street, which is

00:04:06.890 --> 00:04:14.570
obviously more unusual than many others.
But the journey that I made over those 50

00:04:14.570 --> 00:04:23.800
years reflects a journey that
so many women have made in the developed world

00:04:23.800 --> 00:04:33.310
over the 50 years.
And I talk a little bit about my mother and

00:04:33.310 --> 00:04:41.790
my grandmother both of whom
who left school at 14.

00:04:41.790 --> 00:04:51.730
Both of whom who were intelligent women who
had a lot to offer but

00:04:51.730 --> 00:05:05.680
didn't get the opportunities that I was offered.
And both of whom who were absolutely determined

00:05:05.680 --> 00:05:13.590
that I should be able,
and my sister should be able, to take advantage

00:05:13.590 --> 00:05:21.930
of those opportunities.
And I'm very conscious that that's not an

00:05:21.930 --> 00:05:27.180
untypical story, though it
has atypical elements.

00:05:27.180 --> 00:05:35.720
And that's what I wanted to tell.
And I wanted to see that if a girl like me

00:05:35.720 --> 00:05:46.030
coming from working class
Liverpool can get to the White House and to

00:05:46.030 --> 00:05:50.120
meet the Pope, and all the
other things I've done --

00:05:50.120 --> 00:05:59.030
That any girl or any boy actually, given the
right education and the

00:05:59.030 --> 00:06:12.251
right opportunities, can go wherever they
want to go.

00:06:12.251 --> 00:06:25.610
&gt;&gt; So another book describes a journey.
And a lot of people here in this room, some

00:06:25.610 --> 00:06:30.950
of the best and brightest,
are in the early stages of their journey of

00:06:30.950 --> 00:06:35.390
life.
What can you give as advice to all these people

00:06:35.390 --> 00:06:41.340
in terms of what are
some of the things that they should remember

00:06:41.340 --> 00:06:46.340
as they undertake this
journey which you can draw upon from your

00:06:46.340 --> 00:06:47.970
book or your life?

00:06:47.970 --> 00:06:55.050
CHERIE BLAIR: Well, I think first off, never
be too planned.

00:06:55.050 --> 00:07:01.590
I think you always need to make allowances
for the unexpected.

00:07:01.590 --> 00:07:12.090
I'm a great believer in seizing opportunities
as they along and also trying things.

00:07:12.090 --> 00:07:20.610
Now, that's got me into trouble, by the way.
Because sometimes having an open mind and

00:07:20.610 --> 00:07:35.580
trying to try things can get you into trouble.
But on the other hand, the curiosity about

00:07:35.580 --> 00:07:48.550
the world, and what it has
to offer, I think, is something is that gets

00:07:48.550 --> 00:07:55.210
me up every morning even
now.

00:07:55.210 --> 00:07:59.280
&gt;&gt; What else would you say to these people
aspiring to --

00:07:59.280 --> 00:08:06.890
CHERIE BLAIR: Well, these people, of course,
you were telling me

00:08:06.890 --> 00:08:14.940
there're all already high achievers.
They've already had opportunities which other

00:08:14.940 --> 00:08:25.190
people can only dream of.
And the reason they're here, I think, is because

00:08:25.190 --> 00:08:37.370
they actually want to
think of ways to make the sort of opportunities

00:08:37.370 --> 00:08:42.969
they've had available
to everyone else.

00:08:42.969 --> 00:08:49.950
Which is why I said to you I'd love to talk
about technology.

00:08:49.950 --> 00:08:58.740
Because I think technology is really a key
to what we can deliver in

00:08:58.740 --> 00:09:05.210
the 21st Century, which you could've only
dreamed about in centuries

00:09:05.210 --> 00:09:12.180
beforehand.
That's not to say that there are some disadvantages

00:09:12.180 --> 00:09:16.480
with technology but
it's also a huge opportunity.

00:09:16.480 --> 00:09:22.390
&gt;&gt; So let's go to technology and we'll come
back -- we'll keep going

00:09:22.390 --> 00:09:27.240
back and forth depending on what you want
to talk about.

00:09:27.240 --> 00:09:30.430
You've Googled yourself, I presume?
[LAUGHTER]

00:09:30.430 --> 00:09:34.850
We all have.
It's okay.

00:09:34.850 --> 00:09:37.510
We're amongst friends.

00:09:37.510 --> 00:09:48.390
CHERIE BLAIR: No, no.
Of course I've Googled myself but it's a little

00:09:48.390 --> 00:09:59.380
bit sort of uninformative, really, because
all you get, you get the

00:09:59.380 --> 00:10:10.020
whole of the stuff from the Daily Mail, you
know, frankly.

00:10:10.020 --> 00:10:16.800
[LAUGHTER]
You don't want to go there.

00:10:16.800 --> 00:10:25.470
And certainly not if you're me, do you want
to go there.

00:10:25.470 --> 00:10:31.850
And so, yes, of course.
I use Google all the time to find things.

00:10:31.850 --> 00:10:38.580
But also, of course, conscious that sometimes
you find things on Google

00:10:38.580 --> 00:10:44.899
that aren't true not at least if you read
the Daily Mail.

00:10:44.899 --> 00:10:48.330
&gt;&gt; That's true.
Well, you know, we just try and help people

00:10:48.330 --> 00:10:50.940
find information.
We can't validate the information.

00:10:50.940 --> 00:10:52.619
CHERIE BLAIR: You can't validate the information.

00:10:52.619 --> 00:10:55.980
&gt;&gt; We were talking earlier upstairs about
Facebook --

00:10:55.980 --> 00:10:57.420
CHERIE BLAIR: Yep.

00:10:57.420 --> 00:11:06.790
&gt;&gt; And you said that's a bit of dangerous
place for you to go, given

00:11:06.790 --> 00:11:13.910
how many people would be interested to finding
out what you do and

00:11:13.910 --> 00:11:17.100
where you are.
But your kids are on Facebook?

00:11:17.100 --> 00:11:20.510
CHERIE BLAIR: Well, my kids are on Facebook
but from time to time

00:11:20.510 --> 00:11:23.861
they've had to come off Facebook.
Because the problem that they've found is

00:11:23.861 --> 00:11:33.050
that -- they get put --
You go into Facebook, and it's like it's your

00:11:33.050 --> 00:11:41.051
environment.
And that's certainly what they think.

00:11:41.051 --> 00:11:57.310
But the truth is it's also an environment
that the press can get into.

00:11:57.310 --> 00:12:09.709
And so there have times when we then find
that pictures that my

00:12:09.709 --> 00:12:20.700
daughter may have put onto Facebook have then
been taken by the papers

00:12:20.700 --> 00:12:38.560
and published.
And what she might have wanted to share with

00:12:38.560 --> 00:12:51.020
her community in Facebook
particularly in an era what she thought she

00:12:51.020 --> 00:13:00.680
was in a private space, she
doesn't actually want published to her parents,

00:13:00.680 --> 00:13:05.360
frankly.
Not the least to the Daily Mail.

00:13:05.360 --> 00:13:11.899
And so, it is a problem, I think, that if
you're involved in public

00:13:11.899 --> 00:13:19.350
life or if you're a child of someone involved
in public life -- even

00:13:19.350 --> 00:13:27.260
when you're a private person yourself -- that
doesn't mean that other

00:13:27.260 --> 00:13:33.040
people don't think that you're a non-private
person.

00:13:33.040 --> 00:13:44.350
&gt;&gt; But do you think that things can stay private
on the Internet at

00:13:44.350 --> 00:13:52.870
all?
Some of the kids who are there on Facebook

00:13:52.870 --> 00:14:01.390
could end up in public life
five years from now.

00:14:01.390 --> 00:14:10.040
CHERIE BLAIR: Well, I think, it's strange,
isn't it? Because I think

00:14:10.040 --> 00:14:19.850
that people when you use Facebook, when you
use the Internet, do think

00:14:19.850 --> 00:14:21.839
it's private.
I think.

00:14:21.839 --> 00:14:31.810
I mean, they may be wrong about that.
But that's what kind of makes it you're having

00:14:31.810 --> 00:14:36.070
a conversation, you're
relaxed.

00:14:36.070 --> 00:14:48.850
And yes, you think you're sharing it with
your -- whoever it is.

00:14:48.850 --> 00:15:00.770
You were talking about communities self-selecting
so you think you're

00:15:00.770 --> 00:15:07.540
sharing it with a community of like-minded
people.

00:15:07.540 --> 00:15:22.190
But, of course, there's always the opportunity
for you to be sharing it

00:15:22.190 --> 00:15:35.200
with people actually you don't want to be
sharing it with.

00:15:35.200 --> 00:15:49.370
So that's one the challenges of technology
as well as one of the

00:15:49.370 --> 00:15:54.010
opportunities.
It brings all sort of different people together,

00:15:54.010 --> 00:16:01.300
but it also raises
issues about what are the consequences of

00:16:01.300 --> 00:16:05.980
that.
It's not least me talking about me putting

00:16:05.980 --> 00:16:10.420
up a POSIEDON,
again, wanting to do that.

00:16:10.420 --> 00:16:17.630
But being very conscious, of course, because
I want to have -- I want

00:16:17.630 --> 00:16:27.980
to help women get in contact with other women.
I always remember I was doing a speech in

00:16:27.980 --> 00:16:33.519
Russia, and I often do Power
Point presentations of my speeches.

00:16:33.519 --> 00:16:44.779
And I wanted some pictures of Russian women.
So I went into Google and I put in "Russian

00:16:44.779 --> 00:16:46.140
women."
[LAUGHTER]

00:16:46.140 --> 00:17:02.670
And at the time I was -- at the time, I was
still in Number 10.

00:17:02.670 --> 00:17:10.089
And suddenly these, I thought, this is not
what I was thinking.

00:17:10.089 --> 00:17:14.239
This is not the sort of Russian women I was
thinking of.

00:17:14.239 --> 00:17:19.949
And I also thought at any moment now the Downing
Street sort of --

00:17:19.949 --> 00:17:20.949
&gt;&gt; Security people.

00:17:20.949 --> 00:17:24.339
CHERIE BLAIR: Security people are going to
come rushing in here and

00:17:24.339 --> 00:17:29.279
seize the computer, and have me disciplined
for bad behavior.

00:17:29.279 --> 00:17:36.350
Obviously, you have to be pretty careful,
don't you?

00:17:36.350 --> 00:17:42.429
&gt;&gt; So I was having the same conversation with
somebody who has a

00:17:42.429 --> 00:18:02.850
17-year old about being on Facebook.
And he was try to go tell her daughter that

00:18:02.850 --> 00:18:15.900
be careful whatever you put
up there could show up in the public life

00:18:15.900 --> 00:18:26.950
at some point in time.
And she took her dad for the a walk and explained

00:18:26.950 --> 00:18:31.960
that, Dad, this is a
generational gap thing.

00:18:31.960 --> 00:18:41.971
That mostly likely the person who is going
be interviewing me is also going to be on

00:18:41.971 --> 00:18:50.190
Facebook.
So what do you think, just old people like

00:18:50.190 --> 00:19:01.220
you and me who are worried
about this information and the new generation

00:19:01.220 --> 00:19:08.600
really is going to be
different?

00:19:08.600 --> 00:19:18.629
CHERIE BLAIR: Well, I think it goes back to
what I said.

00:19:18.629 --> 00:19:22.850
I think that they're perfectly happy.
Because she'd be perfectly happy for the person

00:19:22.850 --> 00:19:30.620
who is interviewing her
is presumably her age, and is someone -- because

00:19:30.620 --> 00:19:33.210
they're in that
community.

00:19:33.210 --> 00:19:44.029
But would she be so happy --
I know your daughter is a bit young for this

00:19:44.029 --> 00:19:50.379
yet --
but would this 17-year old girl be so happy

00:19:50.379 --> 00:20:00.559
if in fact what
they were saying on Facebook was actually

00:20:00.559 --> 00:20:09.489
on her father's newspaper the
next day with banner headlines saying, you

00:20:09.489 --> 00:20:20.370
know, business executive's
daughter or whatever.

00:20:20.370 --> 00:20:23.740
And that, that's the question.

00:20:23.740 --> 00:20:26.880
&gt;&gt; That's probably not a good idea.

00:20:26.880 --> 00:20:41.820
CHERIE BLAIR: So I don't think that's about
old and young.

00:20:41.820 --> 00:20:48.989
I think it's about not always appreciating
the pitfalls.

00:20:48.989 --> 00:21:01.059
&gt;&gt; So you talked about, you know, your kids
having to be taken off

00:21:01.059 --> 00:21:07.500
Facebook and your being on Facebook not being
a good idea.

00:21:07.500 --> 00:21:12.419
CHERIE BLAIR: No, no. You're persuading me
that I should --

00:21:12.419 --> 00:21:15.480
YouTube, maybe.

00:21:15.480 --> 00:21:21.279
&gt;&gt; I think YouTube.
I think you should definitely have a channel

00:21:21.279 --> 00:21:27.100
on YouTube.
What do you guys think?

00:21:27.100 --> 00:21:34.860
I think she needs to have a channel on YouTube.
We'll talk about that after.

00:21:34.860 --> 00:21:45.789
CHERIE BLAIR: As I told you, I'm always liking
to try things.

00:21:45.789 --> 00:21:57.479
And it's always getting me into trouble.
So when I get into trouble, I'm going to call

00:21:57.479 --> 00:22:01.219
you and blame you.

00:22:01.219 --> 00:22:14.440
&gt;&gt; We're trying to find her a camera slightly
smaller than that that

00:22:14.440 --> 00:22:30.850
she can take with her when she goes -- so
we'll get you on a YouTube

00:22:30.850 --> 00:22:36.890
channel.
But you touched upon something which is the

00:22:36.890 --> 00:22:46.529
notion of public life,
and having your kids having to grow up in

00:22:46.529 --> 00:22:55.249
the media spotlight.
And pretty much you having spent a lot of

00:22:55.249 --> 00:22:58.369
your life now in the media
spotlight.

00:22:58.369 --> 00:23:05.419
How does that impact life and how is that
different?

00:23:05.419 --> 00:23:14.960
CHERIE BLAIR: Well, I think one of the things
I wanted to do again in

00:23:14.960 --> 00:23:20.159
the book was to try and give -- my husband's
going to write --

00:23:20.159 --> 00:23:34.470
he's writing a book and it will come out soon
and in fact will be all about

00:23:34.470 --> 00:23:35.909
the politics --

00:23:35.909 --> 00:23:43.619
&gt;&gt; Which one is going to be better?

00:23:43.619 --> 00:23:50.659
CHERIE BLAIR: Well, it depends what you're
looking for.

00:23:50.659 --> 00:24:04.619
I mean, he's not going to talk about some
of the things that I talked

00:24:04.619 --> 00:24:14.299
about.
And indeed when he read the book I think he

00:24:14.299 --> 00:24:24.519
skipped over quite a few
of the things overwhelmed with embarrassment.

00:24:24.519 --> 00:24:35.039
But I wanted to try and convey something about
what it is like to live

00:24:35.039 --> 00:24:49.820
or to try and live a private life in very
public circumstances.

00:24:49.820 --> 00:25:02.859
And yet in some ways, it's a bit of the story
of my life.

00:25:02.859 --> 00:25:12.409
Because when I was a girl, my father was very
famous for his time.

00:25:12.409 --> 00:25:23.759
He was an actor and he was very fortunate
that he became the sort of

00:25:23.759 --> 00:25:34.700
young interest in what was one of the very
first comedy soap operas in

00:25:34.700 --> 00:25:43.099
Britain in 1960s called "Till Death Do Us
Part."

00:25:43.099 --> 00:25:49.529
And my father literally played himself, really,
was the SCASGET

00:25:49.529 --> 00:25:55.570
scarsgot son-in-law of Warren Mitchell who
was the working class

00:25:55.570 --> 00:26:00.399
racist, East End, opinionated person in the
family.

00:26:00.399 --> 00:26:09.039
And this was very much cutting edge at the
time.

00:26:09.039 --> 00:26:20.799
And so I suddenly found myself at school being
the child of somebody

00:26:20.799 --> 00:26:32.239
very famous.
Then of course I ended up married to somebody

00:26:32.239 --> 00:26:40.080
very famous.
And I still think as I said before, look,

00:26:40.080 --> 00:26:49.850
one day I'll probably be the
mother of somebody very, very famous.

00:26:49.850 --> 00:27:00.450
And so it's an interesting question about
how public life and private

00:27:00.450 --> 00:27:07.539
life coincide.
And when we went into Number 10, my first

00:27:07.539 --> 00:27:19.259
priority was to ensure that
my kids, whatever else I did, was that I preserved

00:27:19.259 --> 00:27:22.739
a private space for
my children.

00:27:22.739 --> 00:27:39.799
And a lot of the time we were in Number 10,
it was quite a struggle to

00:27:39.799 --> 00:27:46.479
try and make that happen.
Because the other thing I wanted to do --

00:27:46.479 --> 00:27:55.799
and because my father was famous, but my father
abandoned my mother and my sister and I with

00:27:55.799 --> 00:28:05.809
his mother in Liverpool and went off to pursue
his career in London.

00:28:05.809 --> 00:28:19.330
So though he was famous, he wasn't at home.
And so I was always at one stake removed.

00:28:19.330 --> 00:28:29.830
I was also very concerned that my children
should feel that whatever

00:28:29.830 --> 00:28:38.929
happened when we were in Number 10 wasn't
something that was being

00:28:38.929 --> 00:28:53.340
imposed on them that they were very much a
part of it.

00:28:53.340 --> 00:28:57.239
And it was a bit of tension there, really,
between making sure that

00:28:57.239 --> 00:29:05.539
your family is involved and feel involved.
And at the same time protecting them from

00:29:05.539 --> 00:29:18.809
the press who say, well, if
you allow your child to be photographed at

00:29:18.809 --> 00:29:29.489
all, it means that we can
then follow them around and do anything we

00:29:29.489 --> 00:29:38.679
like.
Now, as a lawyer, I happen to know that that's

00:29:38.679 --> 00:29:42.429
not how privacy law
works.

00:29:42.429 --> 00:29:49.919
But sometimes there's obviously always a constant
tension between the

00:29:49.919 --> 00:29:58.429
press who always want more, and the personal
who always wants to

00:29:58.429 --> 00:30:00.480
preserve a private space.

00:30:00.480 --> 00:30:05.129
&gt;&gt; What do you think about the UK media?

00:30:05.129 --> 00:30:09.789
CHERIE BLAIR: Oh, I love them.

00:30:09.789 --> 00:30:16.399
&gt;&gt; We are on camera, so.

00:30:16.399 --> 00:30:28.039
CHERIE BLAIR: What you have to understand
is that, you know, a free

00:30:28.039 --> 00:30:33.350
media is a really, really important part of
democracy.

00:30:33.350 --> 00:30:41.289
I totally and utterly accept that.
But I think there's a difference between the

00:30:41.289 --> 00:30:44.749
public interest as we
would define it --

00:30:44.749 --> 00:30:52.370
which is things that the public are legitimately
interested and entitled to know about --

00:30:52.370 --> 00:31:03.440
and things that the public might be interested
in which may, of course, and in fact we know,

00:31:03.440 --> 00:31:15.820
of course, is often stuff which is more about
gossip and celebrity and lifestyle.

00:31:15.820 --> 00:31:29.039
Which wouldn't necessarily be embraced by
the noble cause of ensuring

00:31:29.039 --> 00:31:42.299
democracy functions well.
But because you have a challenging and connected

00:31:42.299 --> 00:31:43.480
media.

00:31:43.480 --> 00:31:52.139
&gt;&gt; So let's go back and try to bridge media
and technology.

00:31:52.139 --> 00:31:59.330
Because all of us here constantly face this
conversation with media

00:31:59.330 --> 00:32:06.269
given that things are more on the Internet,
and there's a lot of

00:32:06.269 --> 00:32:10.220
conversation about newspapers being in trouble?

00:32:10.220 --> 00:32:20.869
CHERIE BLAIR: Well, it's true.
And you know, as a politician, you have to

00:32:20.869 --> 00:32:29.359
engage with the media.
Because democracy is all about the people

00:32:29.359 --> 00:32:33.220
holding their elected
officials accountable.

00:32:33.220 --> 00:32:41.090
And therefore, they need to know what their
elected officials are

00:32:41.090 --> 00:32:44.129
doing.
And the elected officials who have a program

00:32:44.129 --> 00:32:48.019
for government, also want
to actually explain what's going on.

00:32:48.019 --> 00:32:57.289
And that's why the media is very, very important.
On the other hand, if it gets hijacked into

00:32:57.289 --> 00:33:04.349
trivia which is why the
problem that I sometimes encountered, you

00:33:04.349 --> 00:33:12.100
know.
When you government had a serious issue, if

00:33:12.100 --> 00:33:21.879
all that was being talked
about was Cherie's latest gaffe, then actually

00:33:21.879 --> 00:33:34.779
I was damaging something
that I cared very deeply about which was that

00:33:34.779 --> 00:33:44.429
the New Labor Government would be a success
and would deliver.

00:33:44.429 --> 00:33:50.899
And so you know so you're constantly in danger
of being sidetracked in

00:33:50.899 --> 00:33:51.899
your mission.
Now, the newspapers.

00:33:51.899 --> 00:34:00.359
Are we going to need newspapers?
I'm sure we're going to need -- we were just

00:34:00.359 --> 00:34:13.130
talking before, you have
all this information on the Internet.

00:34:13.130 --> 00:34:26.040
And you do need some sort of way of filtering
that information.

00:34:26.040 --> 00:34:31.620
And that's basically what journalists have
done through the centuries

00:34:31.620 --> 00:34:44.310
is help filter the information.
So content, journalistic content, I think

00:34:44.310 --> 00:34:52.700
is very important.
How it's delivered on the other hand, it's

00:34:52.700 --> 00:34:56.521
like a different question,
isn't it?

00:34:56.521 --> 00:35:06.910
Because though I still get my newspaper and
like to read it,

00:35:06.910 --> 00:35:17.510
particularly when I'm traveling, actually,
I will probably go on to the

00:35:17.510 --> 00:35:27.461
Internet and get that information.
I know my kids, of course, get so much of

00:35:27.461 --> 00:35:28.590
their information through the
new media.

00:35:28.590 --> 00:35:37.370
And that's -- that's definitely a generational
thing.

00:35:37.370 --> 00:35:40.980
And a real challenge for the more traditional
media.

00:35:40.980 --> 00:35:42.810
&gt;&gt; So shifting to another Google service,
you mentioned that you've

00:35:42.810 --> 00:35:44.490
looked up your house on Google Street, have
you not?

00:35:44.490 --> 00:35:46.190
CHERIE BLAIR: I have indeed.

00:35:46.190 --> 00:35:52.390
&gt;&gt; But one of your houses is not on Google
Earth and the other one is?

00:35:52.390 --> 00:35:59.530
CHERIE BLAIR: Well, we have a little place
in the country.

00:35:59.530 --> 00:36:07.230
And that's kind of, I think because it's in
the country, you know.

00:36:07.230 --> 00:36:12.670
As far as I gather, your coverage doesn't
cover everything yet.

00:36:12.670 --> 00:36:18.250
But obviously our house in London is very
much on the Google.

00:36:18.250 --> 00:36:19.280
It's very, actually, I was looking for something
 --

00:36:19.280 --> 00:36:25.790
&gt;&gt; It's a nice, sunny, bright day when they're
taking the picture.

00:36:25.790 --> 00:36:41.460
CHERIE BLAIR: Yes, it's a rather nice -- it's
a rather nice picture.

00:36:41.460 --> 00:36:52.150
You go on to the Google Maps, you get your
directions, and then you now

00:36:52.150 --> 00:36:55.370
click on that little button, and you actually
 --

00:36:55.370 --> 00:36:56.370
&gt;&gt; Fantastic.

00:36:56.370 --> 00:36:58.680
CHERIE BLAIR: I was fascinated.

00:36:58.680 --> 00:37:08.020
&gt;&gt; One of the things we talked about was this
balance that one has to

00:37:08.020 --> 00:37:17.920
strike between the role of technology and
privacy for an individual.

00:37:17.920 --> 00:37:31.830
Since you're a lawyer you talk about human
rights and you talk about

00:37:31.830 --> 00:37:37.670
these things.
How do you think we strike that balance right?

00:37:37.670 --> 00:37:40.400
And what should we be thinking about?

00:37:40.400 --> 00:37:44.840
CHERIE BLAIR: Well, you know, I think that
there's never a hundred

00:37:44.840 --> 00:37:56.120
percent right answer about this.
And the more you talk about human rights you

00:37:56.120 --> 00:38:01.890
have to understand, it's
always about balance.

00:38:01.890 --> 00:38:18.220
There are very few absolutes in human rights.
In fact, even the right to life for a long

00:38:18.220 --> 00:38:22.950
time was qualified by
capital punishment.

00:38:22.950 --> 00:38:32.000
Now in Europe now we don't do that qualification
anymore.

00:38:32.000 --> 00:38:40.540
And you can't be a member of the Counsel of
Europe if you have the

00:38:40.540 --> 00:38:43.670
death penalty.
But the fact was even that most fundamental

00:38:43.670 --> 00:38:47.150
right to life did have a
proviso.

00:38:47.150 --> 00:38:52.940
Also torture and slavery are some of the absolute
rights.

00:38:52.940 --> 00:39:03.060
But when you start talk about privacy, the
right to family life, when

00:39:03.060 --> 00:39:10.500
you talk about the rights of association,
free speech --

00:39:10.500 --> 00:39:25.370
all of them come with the requirement that
you can only do that so long as you don't

00:39:25.370 --> 00:39:32.230
interfere with the rights and freedoms of
others.

00:39:32.230 --> 00:39:44.660
And all of them actually come with this notion
of responsibility.

00:39:44.660 --> 00:39:51.250
And you know you can't -- human rights are
much more nuanced than that.

00:39:51.250 --> 00:39:57.170
And then of course, there isn't a hierarchy
of rights.

00:39:57.170 --> 00:40:03.200
So your right to disseminate information comes
up against my right to

00:40:03.200 --> 00:40:06.110
privacy.
And that's about trying to strike a balance.

00:40:06.110 --> 00:40:13.030
And generally speaking, the rule is what you
do is you do the least

00:40:13.030 --> 00:40:20.830
intrusive way of restricting freedom.
Which is commensurate with giving rights and

00:40:20.830 --> 00:40:24.640
freedoms to others.
And is that involves government's trying to

00:40:24.640 --> 00:40:32.300
strike a balance.
It involves individuals and companies trying

00:40:32.300 --> 00:40:36.880
to strike a balance.
And in the end, if the balance, if they can't

00:40:36.880 --> 00:40:41.160
agree on where the
balance is, it involves the courts adjudicating

00:40:41.160 --> 00:40:46.030
as to where the balance
should be struck.

00:40:46.030 --> 00:41:02.740
The advantage, I would say this as a lawyer,
about having it decided in

00:41:02.740 --> 00:41:16.211
the courts is that you do in the court, of
course, have a debate and

00:41:16.211 --> 00:41:29.690
the two sides of the argument are put.
And in the end, the judge has to reach a conclusion

00:41:29.690 --> 00:41:35.070
and when he reaches
that conclusion, he gives you his --

00:41:35.070 --> 00:41:41.050
Why do I say he?
She gives you her reasons.

00:41:41.050 --> 00:41:55.540
And so you have a reasoned judgment, and if
you don't like it you can

00:41:55.540 --> 00:42:08.500
then appeal.
So as someone who believes in the rule of

00:42:08.500 --> 00:42:21.080
law I think that's a good
structure for trying to reach this balance.

00:42:21.080 --> 00:42:25.340
But everybody has a part to play.

00:42:25.340 --> 00:42:29.940
&gt;&gt; We were talking earlier about DNA information,
for example.

00:42:29.940 --> 00:42:48.550
And how if we had access to a lot of DNA information
from around the

00:42:48.550 --> 00:42:55.580
world there's a possibility you could do a
lot to help?

00:42:55.580 --> 00:43:00.490
CHERIE BLAIR: It's definitely, very much so.

00:43:00.490 --> 00:43:09.500
&gt;&gt; And the risk now if you collect everybody's
DNA information that

00:43:09.500 --> 00:43:14.080
intrusion of the people's privacy --

00:43:14.080 --> 00:43:23.210
CHERIE BLAIR: Well, actually, I think that
if it was happening to

00:43:23.210 --> 00:43:30.660
everybody, if everybody had their DNA collected,
then everybody would

00:43:30.660 --> 00:43:37.790
then be in the same boat.
I think the concern has been, and of course

00:43:37.790 --> 00:43:43.270
there's been a recent case
about that, because that it wasn't happening

00:43:43.270 --> 00:43:52.860
to everybody but it was
only happening to certain people.

00:43:52.860 --> 00:44:08.110
And they were people who were in a bit, one
way or another, come into

00:44:08.110 --> 00:44:23.840
connection with the police.
And it was agreed, and doing this balancing

00:44:23.840 --> 00:44:30.840
act that if someone is
actually committed in a crime and has been

00:44:30.840 --> 00:44:39.620
convicted, then clearly that
is right that their DNA should be collected

00:44:39.620 --> 00:44:46.940
and kept.
The question is, however, if they are not

00:44:46.940 --> 00:44:55.160
charged with a crime or if they're acquitted
then what happens?

00:44:55.160 --> 00:45:05.440
And the Europe Court has decided that across
Europe there are

00:45:05.440 --> 00:45:08.830
restrictions on that.
And had an unrestricted access, and they decided

00:45:08.830 --> 00:45:16.890
that they felt that
that wasn't the right balance.

00:45:16.890 --> 00:45:32.310
But actually, I mean I think there could be
a case for everybody

00:45:32.310 --> 00:45:42.920
contributing their DNA because we do know
that the bigger the --

00:45:42.920 --> 00:45:49.660
You know, we had a bigger DNA database than
many other places in Europe

00:45:49.660 --> 00:46:03.680
and because of that, we have been able to
identify people who have

00:46:03.680 --> 00:46:10.140
committed serious crimes.
And it doesn't seem like a day doesn't go

00:46:10.140 --> 00:46:19.070
past or certainly a week
doesn't go past when some DNA evidence has

00:46:19.070 --> 00:46:22.500
either solved the crime
today,

00:46:22.500 --> 00:46:27.480
or as we saw just recently has proved somebody
innocent years after the

00:46:27.480 --> 00:46:31.000
event.
So DNA is a very important tool.

00:46:31.000 --> 00:46:41.670
But it has to be the way you use that tool
has to be done so that there

00:46:41.670 --> 00:46:54.430
are checks and balances.
And so there's a balance between people's

00:46:54.430 --> 00:47:00.610
rights and the rights of the
community to protect itself.

00:47:00.610 --> 00:47:10.510
And you know this is a debate that is absolutely
right that we should

00:47:10.510 --> 00:47:11.510
have.

00:47:11.510 --> 00:47:16.290
&gt;&gt; This is a good thing we're taking pictures
of everybody's house,

00:47:16.290 --> 00:47:22.280
almost everybody.
So we're doing it to everybody is the same

00:47:22.280 --> 00:47:25.530
way, like --

00:47:25.530 --> 00:47:42.140
CHERIE BLAIR: You know in some ways if everybody's
in the same boat

00:47:42.140 --> 00:48:12.660
then you can see that that's a good argument.
I also because I sit as a judge and I see

00:48:12.660 --> 00:48:20.440
in cases in court,
we have quite often we have camera evidence,

00:48:20.440 --> 00:48:31.320
video camera evidence, and it seems to get
better all the time.

00:48:31.320 --> 00:48:37.210
And but -- often, of course, you find that
when it comes to the actual crucial moment

00:48:37.210 --> 00:48:41.810
that's just the bit you can't see.

00:48:41.810 --> 00:48:44.770
&gt;&gt; So let's change topics. You know you're
very passionate about

00:48:44.770 --> 00:48:50.570
equality issues.
And we were talking about Kenya, Rwanda, and

00:48:50.570 --> 00:49:01.560
other parts of the world.
Just give us a sense of all the things you

00:49:01.560 --> 00:49:18.610
see in that area.
What do you think are important things?

00:49:18.610 --> 00:49:24.080
You had a very interesting point about making
sure we are designing

00:49:24.080 --> 00:49:32.630
technology which is of a gender neutral --

00:49:32.630 --> 00:49:40.160
CHERIE BLAIR: Accessible to women, yes.

00:49:40.160 --> 00:49:45.761
&gt;&gt; So I would love to hear your thoughts on
that.

00:49:45.761 --> 00:49:52.350
CHERIE BLAIR: I mean basically it all comes
back to my life story.

00:49:52.350 --> 00:50:03.770
You know, I was a girl brought up by two strong
women who didn't have

00:50:03.770 --> 00:50:19.360
opportunities that I was given.
And you go across the world and you see so

00:50:19.360 --> 00:50:31.130
many wasted opportunities
because in so many cultures and in so many

00:50:31.130 --> 00:50:34.030
societies, women just aren't
valued in the same way as men.

00:50:34.030 --> 00:50:42.890
And we still have a world today where a girl
baby is born in India or

00:50:42.890 --> 00:50:50.890
in China -- or maybe not even born because
they know it's a girl baby

00:50:50.890 --> 00:51:03.030
and so it's aborted simply because of that.
Or is born but then infanticide happens.

00:51:03.030 --> 00:51:15.500
There are plenty of places around the world
where you have a baby, and

00:51:15.500 --> 00:51:42.890
it's a boy and it's a cause for celebration.
And you have a baby and it's a girl, and it's,

00:51:42.890 --> 00:51:50.630
you know, at best,
better luck next time.

00:51:50.630 --> 00:52:22.380
As long as we start from that position where
women are not valued the

00:52:22.380 --> 00:52:45.220
same as men, and we are not actually having
the world as it ought to be

00:52:45.220 --> 00:52:56.370
where women and men are of equal worth and
of equal value and come

00:52:56.370 --> 00:53:07.850
together and work as partners, which is much
more creative.

00:53:07.850 --> 00:53:22.660
I can see here you've got men and women.
And the reality is it's much more creative

00:53:22.660 --> 00:53:26.500
when we use our
complementary skills.

00:53:26.500 --> 00:53:35.030
But, you know, it goes on.
You go to school.

00:53:35.030 --> 00:53:48.810
Girls -- 70 percent of the illiterate children
in the world are girls.

00:53:48.810 --> 00:53:52.830
Why is that?
Because when it comes to making choices about

00:53:52.830 --> 00:54:04.600
which child you educate,
boys are more likely to be educated than girls.

00:54:04.600 --> 00:54:24.320
And yet we know that if you do educate a girl
child you have, she's

00:54:24.320 --> 00:54:31.540
more likely to have fewer children.
She's more likely to marry later.

00:54:31.540 --> 00:54:37.550
She's more likely to make sure her children
are inoculated.

00:54:37.550 --> 00:54:50.420
She's more likely to educate her own children.
So you couldn't have a better investment but

00:54:50.420 --> 00:54:57.580
many, many countries,
we're failing there.

00:54:57.580 --> 00:55:02.100
And then you go on, girls get married too
young.

00:55:02.100 --> 00:55:05.340
Therefore they lose out on education.
Or the women here will know even if not in

00:55:05.340 --> 00:55:13.800
this company,
we could talk about that, but even if it's

00:55:13.800 --> 00:55:14.800
not in this company, in other companies they've
been, you know --

00:55:14.800 --> 00:55:15.800
We find that girls leave university now probably
doing better at

00:55:15.800 --> 00:55:16.800
university than men, that within three years
of women graduating they

00:55:16.800 --> 00:55:17.800
already earn 15 percent less than the equivalent
male graduate.

00:55:17.800 --> 00:55:18.800
Why is that?
We could talk about that.

00:55:18.800 --> 00:55:23.750
And I could go on.
So I think the women's issues.

00:55:23.750 --> 00:55:34.180
You know in the 21st Century, the 21st century
is not the century where

00:55:34.180 --> 00:55:43.910
women become equally respected of equal value
with men then we will

00:55:43.910 --> 00:55:54.190
have failed and that's my passion.
We need to make sure those opportunities are

00:55:54.190 --> 00:56:02.420
there.
So then I think what can I do to do with that?

00:56:02.420 --> 00:56:14.770
I've touched on education being a key.
But lots of things are going on about education

00:56:14.770 --> 00:56:19.970
at the moment, really
good work.

00:56:19.970 --> 00:56:25.500
But the thing that struck me about my own
story in comparison is that

00:56:25.500 --> 00:56:37.420
it was the fact that I was able to be economically
independent, to get

00:56:37.420 --> 00:56:45.960
and to keep any own money and make my own
choices about that, that made

00:56:45.960 --> 00:56:52.090
a big difference.
And so I'm very interested in how we give

00:56:52.090 --> 00:56:55.720
this economic independence to
women.

00:56:55.720 --> 00:57:04.860
And what I want to try and do, is to help
women entrepreneurs, just

00:57:04.860 --> 00:57:12.270
help them link up with other women and grow
their businesses.

00:57:12.270 --> 00:57:21.060
Now by that I don't mean microfinance.
I'm sure everyone in this room knows microfinance

00:57:21.060 --> 00:57:23.470
is a fantastic
success story.

00:57:23.470 --> 00:57:27.869
Not designed originally for women.
Now very much about women.

00:57:27.869 --> 00:57:32.540
But it's still about helping mothers educate,
it's still about keeping

00:57:32.540 --> 00:57:33.990
women within the confines that society has
put to her.

00:57:33.990 --> 00:57:34.990
It's very, very hard.
Not all of those women will be entrepreneurs,

00:57:34.990 --> 00:57:35.990
but it's very hard for
those women who come up through microfinance

00:57:35.990 --> 00:57:36.990
who are entrepreneurs to
gain access to the next stage of growing their

00:57:36.990 --> 00:57:37.990
business.
So I'm concentrating on helping with training

00:57:37.990 --> 00:57:38.990
programs and mentoring
and networking advice for that grade of women

00:57:38.990 --> 00:57:39.990
who can then break out of
their homes and become drivers of development

00:57:39.990 --> 00:57:41.030
in their country.
And for that, I'm sure there's a lot we can

00:57:41.030 --> 00:57:45.020
do in reality.

00:57:45.020 --> 00:57:55.220
&gt;&gt; Let's focus on Africa.
Because as you mentioned earlier, there's

00:57:55.220 --> 00:58:00.360
a lot of stuff that Google is
doing in Africa and wants to do in Africa

00:58:00.360 --> 00:58:05.960
on the infrastructure side.
And you've touched along upon Rwanda and the

00:58:05.960 --> 00:58:06.960
situation there.

00:58:06.960 --> 00:58:16.480
CHERIE BLAIR: Well, I telling you -- would
you like me to tell the

00:58:16.480 --> 00:58:17.480
story?

00:58:17.480 --> 00:58:18.790
&gt;&gt;Yeah, please.

00:58:18.790 --> 00:58:28.960
CHERIE BLAIR: In fact, I describe in the book.
Because I go to, and I went first with Laura

00:58:28.960 --> 00:58:29.960
Bush, just after the
G8 Summit.

00:58:29.960 --> 00:58:32.920
I've been fascinated about Rwanda for a long
time because, of course,

00:58:32.920 --> 00:58:35.590
Rwanda had the genocide.
And it also had an international tribunal

00:58:35.590 --> 00:58:39.320
that dealt with the crimes
against humanity there.

00:58:39.320 --> 00:58:56.490
And as a lawyer, I was very interested in
how as a legal system do you

00:58:56.490 --> 00:59:05.580
cope when society collapses to such an extent
that people who were

00:59:05.580 --> 00:59:12.410
neighbors start doing the most unspeakably
horrible things to each

00:59:12.410 --> 00:59:17.480
other.
So I went to Rwanda and then I went a second

00:59:17.480 --> 00:59:22.700
time.
And my second time they took me up to a village

00:59:22.700 --> 00:59:29.530
in the north of the
country which had been ravaged by the genocide

00:59:29.530 --> 00:59:30.530
and been sort of left
for dead.

00:59:30.530 --> 00:59:34.260
And an American entrepreneurs had come and
helped them set up a

00:59:34.260 --> 00:59:35.260
cooperative.
And they were doing fair trade coffee.

00:59:35.260 --> 00:59:36.260
And in fact, their coffee was being sold in
Sainsbury's here.

00:59:36.260 --> 00:59:39.330
And the women were very much involved in that
project.

00:59:39.330 --> 00:59:41.240
In particular, they trained the women to do
 -- I didn't realize this

00:59:41.240 --> 00:59:42.400
but, you know, like you do wine tasting?
You do the same thing with coffee beans.

00:59:42.400 --> 00:59:43.400
In fact they tried -- I tried to do it but
I was hopeless because you

00:59:43.400 --> 00:59:44.400
have to swill it around your mouth and spit
it out.

00:59:44.400 --> 00:59:45.400
I couldn't get my head around it.
But these women were fantastic.

00:59:45.400 --> 00:59:46.400
But they were some of the best testers and
graders of coffee.

00:59:46.400 --> 00:59:47.400
And I was talking to them, and they were telling
me about how they were

00:59:47.400 --> 00:59:48.400
using the Internet to contact their suppliers.
Because then they would know what the price

00:59:48.400 --> 00:59:49.400
of coffee was going to be
and they could also deal with queries and

00:59:49.400 --> 00:59:50.400
requests.
And they took me to their office where they

00:59:50.400 --> 00:59:51.400
had a computer and they
were doing all this on Skype.

00:59:51.400 --> 00:59:53.441
Here I am in the middle of nowhere in Rwanda,
and here they were

00:59:53.441 --> 00:59:54.441
communicating with Sainsbury's in London and
people in America using

00:59:54.441 --> 00:59:55.441
Skype.
And when they weren't using the computer for

00:59:55.441 --> 00:59:56.441
their business, the women
made it available to the school in the village

00:59:56.441 --> 00:59:57.441
so the kids could use it
for their projects.

00:59:57.441 --> 00:59:58.441
And I thought, you know, isn't this amazing?
That could not have happened 10, 15 years

00:59:58.441 --> 00:59:59.441
ago.
But it just shows the power of technology.

00:59:59.441 --> 01:00:00.441
But one of the things I've subsequently learned,
however, is that

01:00:00.441 --> 01:00:01.441
technology in Africa is becoming available
but it's very man-centered.

01:00:01.441 --> 01:00:02.441
The people who were going in there when they
talk about, you know, you

01:00:02.441 --> 01:00:03.441
can use this for banking.
You can use this for insurance.

01:00:03.441 --> 01:00:04.441
You can use this for communicating with your
markets.

01:00:04.441 --> 01:00:05.441
In their heads, they see a man doing all those
things.

01:00:05.441 --> 01:00:06.441
And if you talk, if they talk about and think
about women using it at

01:00:06.441 --> 01:00:07.441
all,
what they'll say is, oh well, for the women,

01:00:07.441 --> 01:00:08.441
of course, it means
that they can speak to their mother or their

01:00:08.441 --> 01:00:09.441
friends,
you know, more often during the day.

01:00:09.441 --> 01:00:10.441
And so you, it's really important that if
we're talking about access to

01:00:10.441 --> 01:00:11.441
technology in Africa, that we make it so that
it isn't gender centric.

01:00:11.441 --> 01:00:12.441
That it isn't masculine.
That it's actually seen as something that's

01:00:12.441 --> 01:00:13.441
available to women as well
as men.

01:00:13.441 --> 01:00:14.441
Otherwise, we'll have the same problem that
you have about women

01:00:14.441 --> 01:00:15.441
getting access to finance.
The same problem for women having access to

01:00:15.441 --> 01:00:16.441
technology which is a
really important tool to develop your business.

01:00:16.441 --> 01:00:17.441
&gt;&gt; So in that context, another thing which
is I think very common

01:00:17.441 --> 01:00:18.441
amongst the people here, not only they're
all smart and they work for

01:00:18.441 --> 01:00:19.441
Google, is all of them I think I speak for
all of them --

01:00:19.441 --> 01:00:20.441
that they have a passion for trying to change
the world.

01:00:20.441 --> 01:00:21.441
CHERIE BLAIR: Well, me too.

01:00:21.441 --> 01:00:22.441
&gt;&gt; And the question is what advice can you
give them in terms of them

01:00:22.441 --> 01:00:23.441
individually making a contribution towards
changing the world?

01:00:23.441 --> 01:00:24.441
CHERIE BLAIR: Well, I absolutely think it
does start with the

01:00:24.441 --> 01:00:25.441
individual.
I think there's lots of things we can do more

01:00:25.441 --> 01:00:26.441
generally.
But in the end it's about you and your view

01:00:26.441 --> 01:00:27.441
of the world and your
belief in yourself.

01:00:27.441 --> 01:00:28.441
And the fact that you can make a difference.
And if we can teach our children, if we bring

01:00:28.441 --> 01:00:29.441
everybody up to see that
actually each one of us can make a difference.

01:00:29.441 --> 01:00:33.280
And we can do that in all sorts of ways even
in simple things like

01:00:33.280 --> 01:00:34.280
buying the Rwandan coffee.
I've just been involved in a campaign about

01:00:34.280 --> 01:00:35.280
trafficking women and
children across the world.

01:00:35.280 --> 01:00:37.000
And Cadbury's have just announced that from
this summer their Cadbury's

01:00:37.000 --> 01:00:40.619
Dairy Milk is going to be a fair trade product.
Because I don't know if you know, but actually,

01:00:40.619 --> 01:00:41.720
there's a big problem
in West Africa

01:00:41.720 --> 01:00:47.940
where a lot of the cocoa beans come from with
children and others being trafficked into

01:00:47.940 --> 01:00:49.220
there.
Not for sex but as workers in collecting the

01:00:49.220 --> 01:00:50.220
cocoa for which they don't
get paid.

01:00:50.220 --> 01:00:51.220
They're just trapped there.
And there are now ways of ensuring that you

01:00:51.220 --> 01:00:52.220
only buy cocoa beans from
places where that's not happening.

01:00:52.220 --> 01:00:53.290
So taking decisions like that about your Easter
eggs that some of you

01:00:53.290 --> 01:00:54.290
may be thinking of buying would be something
you can do.

01:00:54.290 --> 01:00:55.290
But with the skills and knowledge in this
room, there is so much you

01:00:55.290 --> 01:00:56.290
can do.
So much you can do nationally.

01:00:56.290 --> 01:00:57.290
And I'm sure you probably have schemes already
where you link up with

01:00:57.290 --> 01:00:58.290
schools and you do mentoring and help there.
And then, of course, internationally just

01:00:58.290 --> 01:00:59.290
with what you're saying.
I know you're thinking about Africa at the

01:00:59.290 --> 01:01:00.290
moment so think about some
of these things.

01:01:00.290 --> 01:01:02.860
Think about the women in Africa as well as
the men.

01:01:02.860 --> 01:01:03.860
Think about how much they have to offer.

01:01:03.860 --> 01:01:05.880
&gt;&gt; So in that line, you know, you have all
this energy and all this

01:01:05.880 --> 01:01:06.880
passion.
Where do you draw your inspiration from?

01:01:06.880 --> 01:01:07.880
CHERIE BLAIR: From a number of things.
I think at the end, it does go back to my

01:01:07.880 --> 01:01:08.880
mother and my grandmother.
And seeing them struggle when my father left,

01:01:08.880 --> 01:01:09.880
my mother who had been --
she'd been accepted at RADA.

01:01:09.880 --> 01:01:10.880
And so she'd gone to the Royal Academy of
Dramatic Art in the 50s and

01:01:10.880 --> 01:01:12.130
then she'd -- she'd gone in her vacation.
She got the vacation job and that's how she

01:01:12.130 --> 01:01:14.580
met my father.
He was the juvenile lead male, and she was

01:01:14.580 --> 01:01:15.580
juvenile female lead.
And the next thing you know she's pregnant

01:01:15.580 --> 01:01:16.580
with me.
And then several years on, her husband leaves

01:01:16.580 --> 01:01:17.580
her, and she actually goes and works in a
fish and chips shop.

01:01:17.580 --> 01:01:18.580
In the docks in Seaforth to --
It was the only job she could find where she

01:01:18.580 --> 01:01:19.580
could be able to be there
for us during the day, and still work at night.

01:01:19.580 --> 01:01:20.580
And you think the come down from thinking
you're going to be, you know,

01:01:20.580 --> 01:01:21.580
a glamorous actress to working in a fish and
chips shop in the docks of

01:01:21.580 --> 01:01:22.580
Liverpool.
And yet, she then, you know, pulled herself

01:01:22.580 --> 01:01:23.580
up, got herself a better
job.

01:01:23.580 --> 01:01:24.580
Educated two daughters, both of whom qualified
as lawyers, and ended up

01:01:24.580 --> 01:01:25.580
as the mother-in-law of the Prime Minister.
She's had an incredible life.

01:01:25.580 --> 01:01:26.580
&gt;&gt; So one of the things which we all struggle
with which we find as we

01:01:26.580 --> 01:01:27.580
talk to people is since everybody's ambitious,
and really has

01:01:27.580 --> 01:01:28.580
tremendous amounts of energy and passion in
this room,

01:01:28.580 --> 01:01:29.580
we often struggle with striking the right
balance between work and life.

01:01:29.580 --> 01:01:30.580
And you're a mother of four, you have a professional
career, you have a

01:01:30.580 --> 01:01:31.580
very public life,
as well as you were married to an individual

01:01:31.580 --> 01:01:32.580
who also has a very public life.
And how do you balance all these things so

01:01:32.580 --> 01:01:33.580
that you can maintain your
relationships and -- keep the personal part

01:01:33.580 --> 01:01:34.580
happy?

01:01:34.580 --> 01:01:35.580
CHERIE BLAIR: I would say do as I say but
not necessarily as I do.

01:01:35.580 --> 01:01:36.580
Because that's what I'm going to Malta tomorrow
to talk at a breakfast

01:01:36.580 --> 01:01:37.580
meeting there with the wife of the Prime Minister
of Malta precisely

01:01:37.580 --> 01:01:38.580
about these work/life issues.
And I wish I had the magic formula because

01:01:38.580 --> 01:01:39.580
if I had, wouldn't I be a
wealthy woman?

01:01:39.580 --> 01:01:40.580
But one thing I'm sure of is that this is
not just about women.

01:01:40.580 --> 01:01:41.580
This is absolutely about men and women together.
And if we see this -- if we see work/life

01:01:41.580 --> 01:01:42.580
balance issues as simply a
woman's issue,

01:01:42.580 --> 01:01:43.580
we are completely missing the point.
Because if it's wrong to think of women as

01:01:43.580 --> 01:01:44.580
simply only being able to
offer things within the confines of the home,

01:01:44.580 --> 01:01:45.580
it's equally wrong to think the men actually
are only there to be the breadwinners and

01:01:45.580 --> 01:01:46.580
that they don't care about their family life.
That they don't have a lot to offer.

01:01:46.580 --> 01:01:47.580
It's very important, for example, that our
boys and our girls see

01:01:47.580 --> 01:01:48.580
images of men, you know, of good men,
of active fathers who are contributing not

01:01:48.580 --> 01:01:49.580
just in the work force but in their family
life.

01:01:49.580 --> 01:01:50.580
And, of course, work/life balance isn't just
about bringing up

01:01:50.580 --> 01:01:51.580
children.
It's about what you do about your elderly

01:01:51.580 --> 01:01:52.580
parents.
Something that's becoming more of life issue

01:01:52.580 --> 01:01:53.580
for me as --
and for many people.

01:01:53.580 --> 01:01:54.580
And it's also about just doing the things
that you're passionate about.

01:01:54.580 --> 01:01:55.580
I mean one of the problems I find is just
finding some time when

01:01:55.580 --> 01:01:56.580
actually you're doing something for yourself.
And many of you in this room might sometimes

01:01:56.580 --> 01:01:57.580
find that,
particularly some of you who are parents,

01:01:57.580 --> 01:01:58.580
that you know by the time you've --
One young woman lawyer said to me that you

01:01:58.580 --> 01:01:59.580
know if only my -- the
partners in this firm could understand the

01:01:59.580 --> 01:02:00.580
amount, sheer amount of
effort that I've put into getting all my kids

01:02:00.580 --> 01:02:01.580
out and everything sorted
out before I come into work,

01:02:01.580 --> 01:02:02.580
they would never doubt the commitment that
I had to my work.

01:02:02.580 --> 01:02:03.580
But in the midst of that sometimes you can
lose out on actually making

01:02:03.580 --> 01:02:04.580
sure that you're still a person who's got
needs and rounded

01:02:04.580 --> 01:02:05.580
experiences.
See, it's a really difficult question.

01:02:05.580 --> 01:02:06.580
But it's not just about crushes at work.
That helps.

01:02:06.580 --> 01:02:07.580
It's not just about making sure you have flexi-work.
And it's certainly in my tea company, I presume

01:02:07.580 --> 01:02:08.580
it goes without saying.
I couldn't have done my career.

01:02:08.580 --> 01:02:09.580
I couldn't have carried on as a lawyer if
it wasn't for the fact that I

01:02:09.580 --> 01:02:10.580
was able to use the Internet and the intranet
from 10 Downing Street.

01:02:10.580 --> 01:02:11.580
So I could actually carry on researching my
cases without having to

01:02:11.580 --> 01:02:12.580
actually physically go into the office.
But it's not only about that.

01:02:12.580 --> 01:02:13.580
It's also about an attitude of mind.
It's about accepting that people sometimes

01:02:13.580 --> 01:02:14.580
may want to come into the
workforce.

01:02:14.580 --> 01:02:15.580
So it may well be in your twenties you work
very, very hard.

01:02:15.580 --> 01:02:16.580
But maybe in your sort of childbearing years,
you might want to take a

01:02:16.580 --> 01:02:17.580
to work a bit more flexibly.
But if you do that, it's really important

01:02:17.580 --> 01:02:18.580
that there's a way of getting
back into the workforce.

01:02:18.580 --> 01:02:19.580
It's very important you keep connections,
that you keep your training

01:02:19.580 --> 01:02:20.580
going.
And I myself when I was a young barrister,

01:02:20.580 --> 01:02:21.580
in those days there wasn't
-- we didn't have a maternity policy,

01:02:21.580 --> 01:02:22.580
and I thought at the time, I was so determined
at being the first woman in my chambers --

01:02:22.580 --> 01:02:23.580
I was so determined to show that I could have
children, and still you

01:02:23.580 --> 01:02:24.580
know, still be a good barrister.
And looking back on it now, I think that maybe

01:02:24.580 --> 01:02:25.580
I thought I was changing
the system, and maybe I was just playing to

01:02:25.580 --> 01:02:26.580
the system.

01:02:26.580 --> 01:02:27.580
&gt;&gt; No doubt, yes.

01:02:27.580 --> 01:02:28.580
CHERIE BLAIR: Because I wasn't -- there was
no concession made for the

01:02:28.580 --> 01:02:29.580
fact you're pregnant.
And actually, we need to make some concessions.

01:02:29.580 --> 01:02:30.580
Society needs to make concessions for the
fact of pregnant women need

01:02:30.580 --> 01:02:31.580
to, you know, be essentially protected so
that their babies flourish.

01:02:31.580 --> 01:02:32.580
I mean eventually, with my first son they
actually confined me to the

01:02:32.580 --> 01:02:33.580
hospital bed.
You know, ten days before he was -- well,

01:02:33.580 --> 01:02:34.580
actually, I think a month
before he was due because he wasn't growing

01:02:34.580 --> 01:02:35.580
enough.
Now, in fact, it turned out afterwards that

01:02:35.580 --> 01:02:36.580
all my babies were small, so actually it probably
was the right thing for me.

01:02:36.580 --> 01:02:37.580
But it was kind of -- I was so busy doing
all these things and maybe I

01:02:37.580 --> 01:02:38.580
wasn't looking after myself well enough.
You don't, you shouldn't put women in that

01:02:38.580 --> 01:02:39.580
position.

01:02:39.580 --> 01:02:40.580
&gt;&gt; So I want to ask people to think of questions
and ask questions

01:02:40.580 --> 01:02:41.580
which are on their mind.
But before I do that, you can't come to Google

01:02:41.580 --> 01:02:42.580
and not answer the
questions we ask every new Googlers.

01:02:42.580 --> 01:02:43.580
So you're going to have to help me.
So should we start with the first concert?

01:02:43.580 --> 01:02:44.580
CHERIE BLAIR: My first concert?

01:02:44.580 --> 01:02:45.580
&gt;&gt; Yes.

01:02:45.580 --> 01:02:46.580
CHERIE BLAIR: You mean that I performed in
or that I attended?

01:02:46.580 --> 01:02:47.580
[LAUGHTER]

01:02:47.580 --> 01:02:48.580
&gt;&gt; Both.
I know Tony used to sing in a band.

01:02:48.580 --> 01:02:49.580
CHERIE BLAIR: Oh absolutely.
But I also -- in the 60s it was a big thing

01:02:49.580 --> 01:02:50.580
about folk music.
And Joni Mitchell and Joan Baez.

01:02:50.580 --> 01:02:51.580
I met Joan Baez recently.
I nearly died.

01:02:51.580 --> 01:02:52.580
You know, I said, oh god, I used to sing your
songs.

01:02:52.580 --> 01:02:53.580
I used to play a guitar and sing.
I thought well but probably very, very badly.

01:02:53.580 --> 01:02:54.580
So that's for sure.
So that was the first --

01:02:54.580 --> 01:02:55.580
&gt;&gt; Concert that you performed in.

01:02:55.580 --> 01:02:56.580
CHERIE BLAIR: That I performed in.
And my first concert that I attended?

01:02:56.580 --> 01:02:57.580
That's quite difficult.
I remember going quite early on to see Elton

01:02:57.580 --> 01:02:58.580
John perform.
Later on, of course, he was at that first

01:02:58.580 --> 01:02:59.580
time event at the White
House, and we had, we had with the Clintons.

01:02:59.580 --> 01:03:00.580
And we had a State Visit.
And they put on a fantastic concert that Elton

01:03:00.580 --> 01:03:01.580
John played in and
Stevie Wonder sang My Cherie Amour for me.

01:03:01.580 --> 01:03:02.580
Pretty good.
One of the highlights.

01:03:02.580 --> 01:03:03.580
&gt;&gt; What the other questions that we ask Googlers?
Before you -- go ahead Leanne.

01:03:03.580 --> 01:03:04.580
What are the other Googlers questions?
First date?

01:03:04.580 --> 01:03:05.580
CHERIE BLAIR: First date?

01:03:05.580 --> 01:03:06.580
&gt;&gt; You want to answer that?

01:03:06.580 --> 01:03:07.580
CHERIE BLAIR: Yeah.
Random fact.

01:03:07.580 --> 01:03:08.580
Well, I'll do first date.

01:03:08.580 --> 01:03:09.580
&gt;&gt; Do the first date.
I have already seen you talk about your boyfriends

01:03:09.580 --> 01:03:10.580
in your interview
with the Dominic in the University of California.

01:03:10.580 --> 01:03:11.580
So I think it's out in the public domain.

01:03:11.580 --> 01:03:12.580
CHERIE BLAIR: Well, yes, it was more than
one.

01:03:12.580 --> 01:03:13.580
I had -- surprisingly my husband doesn't like
to me to talk about it.

01:03:13.580 --> 01:03:14.580
There were a few more boyfriends before him.
That's true.

01:03:14.580 --> 01:03:15.580
But actually the -- the first date or the
first time I was kissed was

01:03:15.580 --> 01:03:16.580
when I was about seven.
And --

01:03:16.580 --> 01:03:17.580
&gt;&gt; Okay.
I don't think you're setting the right role

01:03:17.580 --> 01:03:18.580
model here.
