Parliament?

01:03:36.580 --> 01:03:37.580
CHERIE BLAIR: Well, I did stand for Parliament.

01:03:37.580 --> 01:03:38.580
&gt;&gt; So I stand corrected.

01:03:38.580 --> 01:03:39.580
CHERIE BLAIR: I joined the Labor Party because,
well partly, it's kind

01:03:39.580 --> 01:03:40.580
of -- I came from a working class family,
and we always voted Labor.

01:03:40.580 --> 01:03:41.580
And when I was --
When I was 16 they had a teacher at school

01:03:41.580 --> 01:03:42.580
Mrs. Spate, who actually
cause I was at a convent school, but she was

01:03:42.580 --> 01:03:43.580
a quaker.
And she was a member of the Labor Party,

01:03:43.580 --> 01:03:44.580
and she invited me along to meetings.
And years later, she contacted me when I was

01:03:44.580 --> 01:03:45.580
in Number 10.
And subsequent she's -- she died.

01:03:45.580 --> 01:03:46.580
And you know, I still keep in contact with
her daughter who every year

01:03:46.580 --> 01:03:47.580
sends me a little note.
So she was the first person who -- and I joined

01:03:47.580 --> 01:03:48.580
the Labor Party because
I believe in social justice, in equality,

01:03:48.580 --> 01:03:49.580
and its mission to make people like me have
the opportunities that I've been able to have.

01:03:49.580 --> 01:03:50.580
If it hadn't had been for the Labor government
coming in this 1945 and

01:03:50.580 --> 01:03:51.580
changing the system, you know,
a girl like me wouldn't have even got the

01:03:51.580 --> 01:03:52.580
opportunity to go to school.
I was so fortunate because I had a full grant

01:03:52.580 --> 01:03:53.580
to go to university.
Which was -- which was a fantastic opportunity.

01:03:53.580 --> 01:03:54.580
You know, so I think I need to to give something
back.

01:03:54.580 --> 01:03:55.580
And part of the way of giving something back
was to support the Labor

01:03:55.580 --> 01:03:56.580
Party.
And I did stand for Parliament.

01:03:56.580 --> 01:03:57.580
And in 1983, I stood in Thanet North, which
was a seat which is

01:03:57.580 --> 01:03:58.580
basically around Margate and Herne Bay -- which
even in '97 didn't

01:03:58.580 --> 01:03:59.580
become a Labor seat.
So it was never a surefire winner, that's

01:03:59.580 --> 01:04:00.580
for sure.
But there was a brief period when Tony was

01:04:00.580 --> 01:04:01.580
the candidate's spouse.
And this was not a happy period for him.

01:04:01.580 --> 01:04:02.580
[LAUGHTER]
And I tell the story in the book of how just

01:04:02.580 --> 01:04:03.580
in Easter, just before the
May election, or it was June, actually.

01:04:03.580 --> 01:04:04.580
We'd been on holiday, and we came back from
holiday in France into

01:04:04.580 --> 01:04:05.580
Dover.
We went to see my agent to talk about the

01:04:05.580 --> 01:04:06.580
forthcoming election and so
we had lunch.

01:04:06.580 --> 01:04:07.580
And at the end of lunch he said to Tony,
Tony would you mind but Cherie and I need

01:04:07.580 --> 01:04:08.580
to talk a bit about the campaign and business,
so would you mind going out and helping my

01:04:08.580 --> 01:04:09.580
wife wash up?
[LAUGHTER]

01:04:09.580 --> 01:04:10.580
And so he went and helped his wife wash up.
And as he was drying the pots, she said, Tony

01:04:10.580 --> 01:04:11.580
are you interested in politics at all or is
it just that you're doing this to support

01:04:11.580 --> 01:04:12.580
Cherie?
I think that point he was about to divorce

01:04:12.580 --> 01:04:13.580
me.
And I think what Hillary Clinton shows is

01:04:13.580 --> 01:04:14.580
that it's not easy, actually, to be spouse
of a leader.

01:04:14.580 --> 01:04:15.580
And I think she showed that she as a fantastic
First Lady.

01:04:15.580 --> 01:04:16.580
And also had the potential to be a fantastic
President, and now

01:04:16.580 --> 01:04:17.580
fantastic Secretary of State.
But I think Bill, possibly, who was a great

01:04:17.580 --> 01:04:18.580
leader could have done with
a little bit more help about being a support,

01:04:18.580 --> 01:04:19.580
you know, running that
First Lady role.

01:04:19.580 --> 01:04:20.580
It's more difficult than you think.

01:04:20.580 --> 01:04:21.580
&gt;&gt; I think you need to stand up.
[INAUDIBLE]

01:04:21.580 --> 01:04:22.580
&gt;&gt; -- get your views specifically, on recent
calls about cutting

01:04:22.580 --> 01:04:23.580
maternity leave from nine months to six months
to allow partners more

01:04:23.580 --> 01:04:24.580
time off for that to be with their newborn.

01:04:24.580 --> 01:04:25.580
CHERIE BLAIR: Well, I actually think this
is a really interesting idea

01:04:25.580 --> 01:04:26.580
and one which illustrates something I do feel
passionately about.

01:04:26.580 --> 01:04:27.580
Which is, we should be talking about parenting
in the 21st Century.

01:04:27.580 --> 01:04:28.580
And we should not be assuming that this is
all about women.

01:04:28.580 --> 01:04:29.580
And in fact I think sometimes as women we
need to be careful.

01:04:29.580 --> 01:04:30.580
You can often find that you go to the school
gate, you know, if you go

01:04:30.580 --> 01:04:31.580
as a mother, that's fine.
You know, but a father going to the school

01:04:31.580 --> 01:04:32.580
gate, you know,
and half the mothers are whether wondering

01:04:32.580 --> 01:04:33.580
whether he's a child molester.
You know, we need to start being more comfortable

01:04:33.580 --> 01:04:34.580
about the idea that,
you know, men too have a lot to offer in a

01:04:34.580 --> 01:04:35.580
caring role.
And that's a challenge for women.

01:04:35.580 --> 01:04:36.580
Because in a sense I suppose for a long time
we've been placed in this

01:04:36.580 --> 01:04:37.580
area, and now it's about sharing this area.
Having -- having said that, I think I also

01:04:37.580 --> 01:04:38.580
have said that we obviously
need to be do something to support a woman

01:04:38.580 --> 01:04:39.580
when she goes through
essentially what is a physical process, pregnancy,

01:04:39.580 --> 01:04:40.580
and you do need to
make allowances for that.

01:04:40.580 --> 01:04:41.580
Because otherwise, you know, you can endanger
both the mother and the

01:04:41.580 --> 01:04:42.580
child.
So there needs to be a balance there.

01:04:42.580 --> 01:04:43.580
But shared parenting, shared responsibility
is the way ahead.

01:04:43.580 --> 01:04:44.580
And actually I was very lucky.
The ironic thing is that if Tony and I had

01:04:44.580 --> 01:04:45.580
both been barristers,
because he was doing more commercial law,

01:04:45.580 --> 01:04:46.580
and I was doing more of the employment law,
which doesn't get paid as much.

01:04:46.580 --> 01:04:47.580
If I'd fallen pregnant and he was still a
lawyer, it may well have been

01:04:47.580 --> 01:04:48.580
that it would have been actually harder for
me to continue with my

01:04:48.580 --> 01:04:49.580
work.
But the fact was that as I was fighting that

01:04:49.580 --> 01:04:50.580
election in 1983, he went
off and got the Sedgefield seat which was

01:04:50.580 --> 01:04:51.580
a safe seat.
And I discovered I didn't -- I thought I was

01:04:51.580 --> 01:04:52.580
just in distress,
but it turned out that I was actually pregnant

01:04:52.580 --> 01:04:53.580
with my first child at that point.
But because Tony then had become an MP, I

01:04:53.580 --> 01:04:54.580
also found myself then being
the main breadwinner.

01:04:54.580 --> 01:04:55.580
And so to that extent, there was a financial
incentive for me to carry

01:04:55.580 --> 01:04:56.580
on working.
And Tony because he was an opposition MP,

01:04:56.580 --> 01:04:57.580
and therefore wasn't in
government, had actually slightly more time

01:04:57.580 --> 01:04:58.580
to be a hands-on father.
And he was -- you know, he always jokes and

01:04:58.580 --> 01:04:59.580
unkindly shares with many
people that I'm, once I get to sleep at night,

01:04:59.580 --> 01:05:00.580
you kind of have to
dynamite me out of bed.

01:05:00.580 --> 01:05:01.580
And so often at nighttime, when the children
were crying it would be

01:05:01.580 --> 01:05:02.580
Tony who would get up and then he'd bring
the baby to me.

01:05:02.580 --> 01:05:03.580
And you know I would then feed, feed the baby.
And you know he was, he was definitely changing

01:05:03.580 --> 01:05:04.580
nappies long before it
was fashionable.

01:05:04.580 --> 01:05:05.580
Of course, it became more difficult when Leo
came along because he was

01:05:05.580 --> 01:05:06.580
suddenly Prime Minister.
And you know I was wanting to persuade him

01:05:06.580 --> 01:05:07.580
to take a paternity leave.
And of course Leo did very well because he

01:05:07.580 --> 01:05:08.580
was actually born early on a
Friday at a week which actually was a Parliamentary

01:05:08.580 --> 01:05:09.580
recess week.
And so there was no -- there was no question

01:05:09.580 --> 01:05:10.580
time.
And so Tony was able --

01:05:10.580 --> 01:05:11.580
He didn't take -- obviously he kept taking
phone calls.

01:05:11.580 --> 01:05:12.580
And he worked on his boxes but he did base
himself up in the flat for

01:05:12.580 --> 01:05:13.580
that week.
And the fact was as soon as Leo was born,

01:05:13.580 --> 01:05:14.580
he wanted to be there.
As those of you who are fathers will know

01:05:14.580 --> 01:05:15.580
that feeling, I'm sure.
And those of you who will become fathers will

01:05:15.580 --> 01:05:16.580
experience it, too.
You want to be able to share in this new life

01:05:16.580 --> 01:05:17.580
which the two of you have
created together.

01:05:17.580 --> 01:05:18.580
That's really important.

01:05:18.580 --> 01:05:19.580
[INAUDIBLE QUESTION]
[PAUSE]

01:05:19.580 --> 01:05:20.580
CHERIE BLAIR: Well, I think there's -- there
are two points there.

01:05:20.580 --> 01:05:21.580
One is the issue of corruption, and what in
the speak we call

01:05:21.580 --> 01:05:22.580
"governance issues."
And it's actually something that Tony feels

01:05:22.580 --> 01:05:23.580
very passionately
about as well.

01:05:23.580 --> 01:05:24.580
And in fact, he has, as part of his work that
he's doing now, a

01:05:24.580 --> 01:05:25.580
charity.
And at the moment they're working both in

01:05:25.580 --> 01:05:26.580
Rwanda and in Sierra Leone.
And their main purpose is trying to help with

01:05:26.580 --> 01:05:27.580
setting up and supporting
a proper system of governance.

01:05:27.580 --> 01:05:28.580
Which is particularly helping in both cases
to run the Office of the

01:05:28.580 --> 01:05:29.580
President and Prime Minister
in the countries in a way which is transparent,

01:05:29.580 --> 01:05:30.580
which is open, corruption-free, and efficient.
Efficient actually is really quite important,

01:05:30.580 --> 01:05:31.580
as you can imagine.
I, myself, am interested in how we can use

01:05:31.580 --> 01:05:32.580
the law to help with that.
Because in many of these countries like Rwanda,

01:05:32.580 --> 01:05:33.580
for example, after the
genocides,

01:05:33.580 --> 01:05:34.580
there were only about 15 laws in the entire
country.

01:05:34.580 --> 01:05:35.580
I mean, that's a real challenge to try and
build up a legal system from

01:05:35.580 --> 01:05:36.580
scratch.
And other thing I'm convinced of is that once

01:05:36.580 --> 01:05:37.580
you get corruption in the
system, it's very, very damaging.

01:05:37.580 --> 01:05:38.580
And it's, it's a very precious thing a corrupt-free
bureaucracy, a

01:05:38.580 --> 01:05:39.580
corrupt-free judiciary.
And once you have that undermined, it takes

01:05:39.580 --> 01:05:40.580
a long time to right.
So it's a really, it's a really important

01:05:40.580 --> 01:05:41.580
issue.
And it's quite complicated and difficult subject

01:05:41.580 --> 01:05:42.580
to tackle.
As for what we do about development, well,

01:05:42.580 --> 01:05:43.580
I think one thing we've
certainly learned --

01:05:43.580 --> 01:05:44.580
And if you listen to someone like Muhammad
Yunus, he will tell you this

01:05:44.580 --> 01:05:45.580
as well, that handouts are not as good as
hand ups.

01:05:45.580 --> 01:05:46.580
Imposing things on people without consulting
them doesn't work.

01:05:46.580 --> 01:05:47.580
So if you're going to go in, what you must
do is you must consult the

01:05:47.580 --> 01:05:48.580
local community.
You must make sure the local community have

01:05:48.580 --> 01:05:49.580
a sense of ownership in it.
If possible, involve the local community in

01:05:49.580 --> 01:05:50.580
the --
If you're talking about digging a well, or

01:05:50.580 --> 01:05:51.580
laying a road, you know, so
that the jobs actually go to the local people.

01:05:51.580 --> 01:05:52.580
It's also about even at a higher level, when
you're going in, lots of

01:05:52.580 --> 01:05:53.580
countries have lots of consultants.
It's really important that the consultants

01:05:53.580 --> 01:05:54.580
actually transfer the
knowledge, and leave it in the country.

01:05:54.580 --> 01:05:55.580
Rather than having the knowledge, going in,
doing a project, and then

01:05:55.580 --> 01:05:56.580
taking the knowledge out again.
So it's all about capacity building.

01:05:56.580 --> 01:05:57.580
It's all about helping people, whether it's
a government or actually

01:05:57.580 --> 01:05:58.580
individuals, help themselves because there's
a dignity in that.

01:05:58.580 --> 01:05:59.580
And there's a learning experience in that
which, sometimes aid projects haven't always

01:05:59.580 --> 01:06:00.580
encouraged.
[PAUSE]

01:06:00.580 --> 01:06:01.580
&gt;&gt; Thanks. We touched on Street View earlier.
And as you know, some parties in this country

01:06:01.580 --> 01:06:02.580
have reacted quite
strongly against Street View even going so

01:06:02.580 --> 01:06:03.580
far as to ask for it to be
shut down.

01:06:03.580 --> 01:06:04.580
And some have pointed out the irony that we
live in a country where the

01:06:04.580 --> 01:06:05.580
public accepts, with little protest,
a government who collects vast amounts of

01:06:05.580 --> 01:06:06.580
data.
Recently talking about tracking social networks

01:06:06.580 --> 01:06:07.580
and e-mails and text
messages in the name of national security.

01:06:07.580 --> 01:06:08.580
What are your views on that?
Should we be more worried about the government,

01:06:08.580 --> 01:06:09.580
less worried freeing
information to the public?

01:06:09.580 --> 01:06:10.580
CHERIE BLAIR: Well, I think it's what I said
before about the whole

01:06:10.580 --> 01:06:11.580
question about privacy and rights to information.
It's about getting the balance right.

01:06:11.580 --> 01:06:12.580
And, you know, when you have any of these
issues I think you have to

01:06:12.580 --> 01:06:13.580
say well what -- what are we collecting this
information for?

01:06:13.580 --> 01:06:14.580
Is it for a good purpose?
Cause if it isn't, then we shouldn't be doing

01:06:14.580 --> 01:06:15.580
it anyway.
That's the first thing.

01:06:15.580 --> 01:06:16.580
But let's assume therefore that there is a
legitimate purpose in that.

01:06:16.580 --> 01:06:17.580
Are we then --
So the next question then is are we doing

01:06:17.580 --> 01:06:18.580
in it the least intrusive
way?

01:06:18.580 --> 01:06:19.580
And that may involve, for example, as I gather
you now do, allowing

01:06:19.580 --> 01:06:20.580
people if they do object, to opt out.
Or it may involve actually saying you have

01:06:20.580 --> 01:06:21.580
to have people opt in.
I mean, these are these are the questions

01:06:21.580 --> 01:06:22.580
that need to be debated.
Lawyers love the concept of proportionality.

01:06:22.580 --> 01:06:23.580
Is it proportional?
So it's that idea you don't use the sledge

01:06:23.580 --> 01:06:24.580
hammer to crack a nut.
And actually, it's all about a scale and a

01:06:24.580 --> 01:06:25.580
balance.
And it's about bringing the -- the balance

01:06:25.580 --> 01:06:26.580
to the right tipping point.
And that may change over time.

01:06:26.580 --> 01:06:27.580
And it's about debating.
It's about being transparent in what you're

01:06:27.580 --> 01:06:28.580
doing.
And it's about making sure that you can justify

01:06:28.580 --> 01:06:29.580
what you're doing as
actually benefitting people, cause if you

01:06:29.580 --> 01:06:30.580
can't, then you shouldn't be
doing it.

01:06:30.580 --> 01:06:31.580
&gt;&gt; We prefer the idea of opt out as opposed
to opt in, because it

01:06:31.580 --> 01:06:32.580
becomes very onerous.
Hey, you know, I'm planning a building, you

01:06:32.580 --> 01:06:33.580
have a choice to object as opposed to --

01:06:33.580 --> 01:06:34.580
CHERIE BLAIR: But you would.
But there needs to be a discussion about whether

01:06:34.580 --> 01:06:35.580
 --
Because you have also a commercial imperative.

01:06:35.580 --> 01:06:36.580
And so you know, is your commercial imperative
furthering on or not

01:06:36.580 --> 01:06:37.580
furthering the public interest?
And the important thing is to debate that

01:06:37.580 --> 01:06:38.580
and to debate you it
openly.

01:06:38.580 --> 01:06:39.580
But I think the disadvantage is in somehow,
sometimes I don't like some

01:06:39.580 --> 01:06:40.580
of the things that are in the press is this
kind of scare mongering

01:06:40.580 --> 01:06:41.580
about things.
Because actually sharing information, having

01:06:41.580 --> 01:06:42.580
information available is a
very powerful tool for good as well as for

01:06:42.580 --> 01:06:43.580
bad.
And therefore we shouldn't, we shouldn't be

01:06:43.580 --> 01:06:44.580
silly about this.
But we have to make sure that the proper checks

01:06:44.580 --> 01:06:45.580
and balances is in
place.

01:06:45.580 --> 01:06:46.580
&gt;&gt; Hi, you and I are both Catholics, I believe.

01:06:46.580 --> 01:06:47.580
CHERIE BLAIR: Ah, yes.

01:06:47.580 --> 01:06:48.580
&gt;&gt; How does it make you feel when you see
Cardinal Ratzinger or Pope

01:06:48.580 --> 01:06:49.580
Benedict going to Africa, to many countries
which have double digit HIV

01:06:49.580 --> 01:06:50.580
infection rates, telling people not to use
condoms.

01:06:50.580 --> 01:06:51.580
And what do you think Catholics should actually
do about that?

01:06:51.580 --> 01:06:52.580
CHERIE BLAIR: I think it makes me rather sad.
And I think that there is a real question,

01:06:52.580 --> 01:06:53.580
and a real dividing line between contraception,
which I see as a way of preventing life beginning,

01:06:53.580 --> 01:06:54.580
and abortion, which is about terminating a
life that has begun.

01:06:54.580 --> 01:06:55.580
I think there is a distinction between the
two.

01:06:55.580 --> 01:06:56.580
And that sometimes the condom issue doesn't
add clarity to that

01:06:56.580 --> 01:06:57.580
distinction but rather makes it a lot more
muddy.

01:06:57.580 --> 01:06:58.580
My own view is, and I've said this before,
that condoms are absolutely

01:06:58.580 --> 01:06:59.580
essential in the fight against AIDS.
And that we should be encouraging people to

01:06:59.580 --> 01:07:00.580
use them.
But, we also must understand that promiscuity

01:07:00.580 --> 01:07:01.580
is a problem.
That actually sex is about relationships and

01:07:01.580 --> 01:07:02.580
respect.
And that, that if you have a culture which

01:07:02.580 --> 01:07:03.580
sees sex as just a
commodity, if we, that this is not necessarily

01:07:03.580 --> 01:07:04.580
 --
Well, this is not necessarily a bad thing,

01:07:04.580 --> 01:07:05.580
it is a bad thing.
And therefore, how we encourage people to

01:07:05.580 --> 01:07:06.580
behave responsibly,
and part of behaving responsibly to my mind

01:07:06.580 --> 01:07:07.580
anyway
particularly in a country where there is an

01:07:07.580 --> 01:07:08.580
endemic AIDS epidemic is to use safe sex methods.
But responsible sex is also really important.

01:07:08.580 --> 01:07:09.580
And the idea that anything goes --
And the Pope, of course, was talking about

01:07:09.580 --> 01:07:10.580
how promiscuity is a
problem.

01:07:10.580 --> 01:07:11.580
And it is a problem, and he's right to draw
attention to that.

01:07:11.580 --> 01:07:12.580
Again, we're talking about striking the right
balance, having a

01:07:12.580 --> 01:07:13.580
discussion.
And making sure that we don't throw the sort

01:07:13.580 --> 01:07:14.580
of dignity baby out with the bath water.
The dignity of individuals and the respect

01:07:14.580 --> 01:07:15.580
there should be between a
man and a woman in all relationships including

01:07:15.580 --> 01:07:16.580
sexual.
And actually for that matter, between same-sex

01:07:16.580 --> 01:07:17.580
partners.

01:07:17.580 --> 01:07:17.588
&gt;&gt; On that note, thank you very much.
[APPLAUSE]

